### 2. Register in `Program.cs`

Add these lines to your existing `Program.cs`:

```csharp
// ── Services ──────────────────────────────────
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<ApiExceptionHandler>();
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();

// ── Middleware (order matters — place before routing) ──
app.UseExceptionHandler();   // catches exceptions → Problem Details
app.UseStatusCodePages();    // converts bare 4xx/5xx → Problem Details
```

**How it works:**

| Exception | HTTP Status | Problem Details `title` |
|---|---|---|
| `KeyNotFoundException` | 404 | Not Found |
| `ArgumentException` | 400 | Bad Request |
| `InvalidOperationException` | 409 | Conflict |
| Anything else | 500 | Safe generic error (no leak) |

- `IExceptionHandler` intercepts exceptions globally — no per-endpoint `try-catch` needed.
- Mapped exceptions get a specific status code and are logged as warnings.
- Unmapped exceptions fall through (`return false`), and the default `UseExceptionHandler` middleware returns a **500** with `AddProblemDetails()` formatting — no `exception.Message` exposed.
- `UseStatusCodePages()` ensures non-exception error status codes (e.g., a manual `404`) also get Problem Details format.

Your endpoints stay clean — just throw the appropriate exception:

```csharp
app.MapGet("/api/products/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    // This automatically becomes a 404 Problem Details response
    throw new KeyNotFoundException($"Product {id} not found");
});
```
